## OTA Update Versioning

When deploying an OTA update via `npx eas update`:

1. Before running the EAS update command, increment the `BUILD_TAG` in `components/update-version-banner.tsx` from the current version to the next sequential version (e.g. v27 → v28 → v29).
2. The BUILD_TAG format is: `v{NUMBER}-{short-description}` where the description is 2-4 lowercase words separated by hyphens summarizing the main change (e.g. `v27-camera-zoom-fix`, `v28-load-refresh`).
3. Include the updated `components/update-version-banner.tsx` in the git commit.
4. Use the BUILD_TAG as the `--message` parameter for the `eas update` command (e.g. `--message "v27-camera-zoom-fix"`).
5. The current version is tracked by the `BUILD_TAG` constant on line 6 of `components/update-version-banner.tsx`. Always read this file first to determine the current version number before incrementing.
6. **ALWAYS push to all three EAS Update branches** (`production`, `development`, `preview`) so every build channel — internal/dev clients, beta testers, and store builds — receives the update. Using `--auto` instead picks the current git branch (usually `main`), which goes nowhere on installed builds. Correct sequence:
   ```bash
   npx eas update --branch production  --message "v{N}-{desc}"
   npx eas update --branch development --message "v{N}-{desc}"
   npx eas update --branch preview     --message "v{N}-{desc}"
   ```
   Channel-to-branch mapping is defined in `eas.json` (each build profile sets `channel`, and EAS Update branches are named to match).
